This will require (in the next 2 years):
1. A virtual end to the civil war, to the extent elections could take place (likely brokered by world powers with individual goals);
2. A willingness from Assad, and his allies who may fear elections in general, to hold elections;
3. Or Assad's fall;
4. Candidates;
5. Election infrastructure I doubt all of this will occur within two years, especially considering the continued existence of ISIS. Were ISIS to fall in Syria, who's to say that Assad will also be gone as well, and that there will be a resistance left to fight him. Battle fatigue may incline the population toward staying with Assad past this deadline, or into the future. While his actions are far worse that his father's, Assad's strong arm tactics mimic his father's destruction of villages. These actions didn't result in the Sr.'s removal from power.
